/***************************************************************************
	An incant version of Awk???
***************************************************************************/
incant looks a little like awk on steroids. However, there is one big difference. awk processes input, running it against its patterns. If the patterns match, awk fires the pattern actions against what it matched, and then it carries on processing input.
    Unlike awk, incant works like a compiler. That is, it matches input against a set of rules until it encounters input that does not match its rule set, at which point it quits.
        How about we provide an awk like alternative for incant that runs its rules against input, skips over does not match stuff, and continues until it runs out of input (or until it is encounters input that tells it to stop)
        awk actions are just incant actions
    How would it work?
        An awk rule would process input against its members (all rules).
        It would have to have a what to do if nothing matches rule (like advance to the next new line and continue)
    Treat each line of input as a possible command, or like a record to be matched against (does this record have this or that and maybe something else). If so then somebody DO something (do what, who do, and to what). Match criteria might be a wee bit of fuzzy logic, perhaps determining parameters; what to do would be specific????
            Shades of my old java tool for specifying procedures used to match against a list of procedures and fire off the one that matched parameters provided
    The when nothing matches rule is a general case that the incant grammar does not handle. Perhaps we can change the grammar to fix that?

/***************************************************************************
    How to load fixed length fields
***************************************************************************/
How to define fixed length fields, which can be a type, string, or number. All three options have a count that can be used as the input length. Fixed length fields would be defined like:
        record isRule fixed
            countField=5;
            skipOver- =25;
            numberField=10.0;
            stringField="some string of length desired";
            typeField=someType;; // someType could be fRAME for instance
Note that the fixed length fields are defined as attributes. When the record rule is run its attributes are processed in order and the parser process each as a fixed length field and the results are stashed in the record label.
Not sure I like this but I like the idea of being able to parse fixed length fields
    
